{"award_age":87.0,"bio_image":"full\/6b00f9f2101d2d0a66cb6e1e57058f9eac914046.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1879-10-05T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1970-02-16T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/en\/thumb\/7\/74\/Peyton_Rous_nobel.jpg\/180px-Peyton_Rous_nobel.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Peyton_Rous","mini_bio":"<p><b>(Francis) Peyton Rous,<\/b> <span style=\"font-size:85%;\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Foreign_Member_of_the_Royal_Society\" title=\"Foreign Member of the Royal Society\" class=\"mw-redirect\">ForMemRS<\/a><\/span><sup id=\"cite_ref-frs_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Peyton_Rous#cite_note-frs-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> (October 5, 1879 \u2013 February 16, 1970) was born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Woodlawn,_Baltimore_County,_Maryland\" title=\"Woodlawn, Baltimore County, Maryland\">Woodlawn, Maryland<\/a> in 1879 and received his B.A. and M.D. from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Johns_Hopkins_University\" title=\"Johns Hopkins University\">Johns Hopkins University<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Peyton_Rous#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was involved in the discovery of the role of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Virus\" title=\"Virus\">viruses<\/a> in the transmission of certain types of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cancer\" title=\"Cancer\">cancer<\/a>. In 1966 he was awarded a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize\" title=\"Nobel Prize\">Nobel Prize<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> for his work.<\/p><p>In 1911, as a pathologist he made his seminal observation, that a malignant tumor (specifically, a sarcoma) growing on a domestic chicken could be transferred to another fowl simply by exposing the healthy bird to a cell-free filtrate.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Peyton_Rous#cite_note-3\"><span>[<\/span>3<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Peyton_Rous#cite_note-4\"><span>[<\/span>4<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> This finding, that cancer could be transmitted by a virus (now known as the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rous_sarcoma_virus\" title=\"Rous sarcoma virus\">Rous sarcoma virus<\/a>, a retrovirus), was widely discredited by most of the field's experts at that time. Since he was a relative newcomer, it was several years before anyone even tried to replicate his prescient results. Although clearly some influential researchers were impressed enough to nominate him to the Nobel Committee as early as 1926 (and in many subsequent years, until he finally received the award, 40 years later\u2014this may be a record for the time between a discovery and a Nobel Prize).<\/p><p>In his later life he wrote biographies of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Simon_Flexner\" title=\"Simon Flexner\">Simon Flexner<\/a><sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Peyton_Rous#cite_note-5\"><span>[<\/span>5<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Karl_Landsteiner\" title=\"Karl Landsteiner\">Karl Landsteiner<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Peyton_Rous#cite_note-6\"><span>[<\/span>6<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>His wife Marion died in 1985. His daughter <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Marni_Hodgkin\" title=\"Marni Hodgkin\">Marni Hodgkin<\/a> was a children's book editor, and the wife of another Nobel Prize winner, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Alan_Hodgkin\" title=\"Alan Hodgkin\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Alan Hodgkin<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Francis_Peyton_Rous#cite_note-7\"><span>[<\/span>7<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Francis Peyton Rous","place_of_birth":"Baltimore, Maryland","place_of_death":"New York City","text":"Francis Peyton Rous , Physiology or Medicine, 1966","year":1966.0}